</li><li id="tree_64186726" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64186726" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64186726" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64186726" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64186726" name="comment_link_64186726" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204088&amp;cid=64186726" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64186726)" >Counterproductive</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64186726" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64186726); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~IDemand2HaveSumBooze">IDemand2HaveSumBooze</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~IDemand2HaveSumBooze">( 9493913 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64186726">		
		on Thursday January 25, 2024 @05:57AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204088&amp;cid=64186726">#64186726</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64186726"><p>I think the intentions behind things like the Doomsday clock are good, it's meant to draw attention to some of the threats we're facing. However the overdramatic nature of that stuff makes it counterproductive to that goal. People stop taking you seriously, and then they start listening to "we don't need no experts" and "it's all scaremongering" type of people. What scientists should be doing is describing threats in an accurate, objective, dispassionate and, well, scientific manner. It's what they're good at.</p><p>It's like people who claim that global warming will lead to humanity's extinction. As things stang it looks like a lot of people will die and others will live, but not as well as they used to, but humanity as a whole and human civilization will certainly survive. Unless some weird feedback loop is triggered, but that seems very unlikely as far as I understand. Predicting the end of humanity just makes you look like a loon and pushes people towards the "it's all just a bit of weather" shills.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64186726">
