</li><li id="tree_64187422" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64187422" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64187422" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64187422" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64187422" name="comment_link_64187422" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204088&amp;cid=64187422" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64187422)" >Contradictions of Bulletin of the Atomic Scientist</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64187422" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64187422); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~MacMann">MacMann</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~MacMann">( 7518492 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64187422">		
		on Thursday January 25, 2024 @11:26AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204088&amp;cid=64187422">#64187422</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64187422"><p>Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists is a contradictory organization, they want to be rid of nuclear weapons and also be rid of nuclear power.  Well, now that this genie is out of the bottle there's no putting it back.</p><p>Once weapon grade plutonium is created it is difficult to destroy by any means other than neutron bombardment.  Plutonium will decay away in time, but a very long time.  Of the different series of decay chains Pu-239 is on the shortest one but that just means we can't find much of it in nature on a planet that is billions of years old such as Earth.  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decay_chain#Actinium_series" title="wikipedia.org">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...</a> [wikipedia.org]</p><p>We can take the material needed to make nuclear weapons and spread it out real thin to make it difficult to gather back together again, a process called "down blending", but at some point the process is pointless because if people want to make nuclear weapons they can just go looking in nature for some thinly spread out U-235 and concentrate that instead.  Do these scientists not realize that the first nuclear weapon used was produced without a nuclear reactor?  Do these scientists know that there's no stopping people from digging in their own backyard for this material?  Do they not know that the general plans for nuclear weapons have been published widely for decades and with a few dedicated technicians, engineers, and scientists eventually they will just fill in the gaps on their own?  In the 1940s nobody was even sure that a nuclear weapon was possible, now that the theory is proven it is an engineering exercise.</p><p>They associate nuclear power plants with nuclear weapons, which is nonsense.  Do we associate nuclear weapons with nuclear medicine?  I'm pretty sure that we will not easily abandon nuclear medicine, that's just too useful to walk away from no matter how much this knowledge could be used to make weapons.  Do we associate electric power with electric chairs?  Is there no peaceful use of petroleum or is every oil drill just too much a risk of someone making napalm to allow it?  No matter that people need that fuel for agricultural tractors and modern farming techniques, we should let people starve than risk someone making weapons from that fuel, that's the kind of thinking Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists is advocating, it is better that people freeze and starve than allow nuclear power plants be built.</p><p>If these people understood science then they should understand that the only way to peacefully rid the world of the weapon grade nuclear material on this planet is to consume it as fuel in a nuclear power reactor.  So long as these morons advocate we walk away from the safest, and lowest CO2 emitting, energy source we've ever developed they are to be ignored.  Their "doomsday clock" is nonsense, a propaganda tool to get attention for their contradictory purpose for existence.</p><p>Had they remained an organization opposed to nuclear weapons, and not expanded into climate change, then they might have a reason for existence.  But then as the Cold War ended in the 1990s they didn't have much reason to exist because the threat of nuclear weapons effectively evaporated then so they had to think up a new reason to keep going.  As an organization that wants to end global warming they just get lost in the noise of other such organizations.  As an organization opposed to nuclear power they get lost in that noise.  As an organization that opposes nuclear power and global warming they have become an organization lacking in any real science, they contradict themselves in their purpose statement.  I lump them in with World Nuclear Industry Status Report as an organization motivated by an opposition to science. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Nuclear_Industry_Status_Report" title="wikipedia.org">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...</a> [wikipedia.org]</p><p>Ignore the "doomsday clock", it's as accurate of a measure of the threats we face as a stopped clock is at telling time.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64187422">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64187422" class="btn link" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23204088&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64187422" onclick="D2.replyTo(64187422); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
